@SBK
For the most part, all Chinese dialects/languages are written the same, at least when it comes to formal documents. However, a transcription of colloquial speech would have some differences in vocabulary and grammar. For example, in Mandarin and standard written Chinese, “I don’t have any money” would be 我沒有錢 (“Wǒ méi yǒu qián” in Mandarin and “Ngo mut jau cin” in Cantonese), but typically a Cantonese speaker would actually say 我冇錢 (“Ngo mou cin”), using 冇 instead of 沒有 to express “to not have.”

Since the latter half of the twentieth century, there is also a distinction between traditional and simplified characters, following orthographic reforms in Mainland China. Simplified characters are used in the PRC mainland and Singapore, while traditional characters are used in Hong Kong, Macau, Taiwan, and among many overseas Chinese communities. “People’s Republic of China” is written as 中华人民共和国 in simplified characters and as 中華人共和國 in traditional characters. The distinction between the two types of characters is irrespective of dialect: a Mandarin speaker from Taipei and a Cantonese speaker from Hong Kong would both use traditional characters, while a Mandarin speaker from Beijing and a Cantonese speaker from Guangzhou would both use simplified characters. The differences between the two types of characters are larger than the differences between British and American spelling, but if you can read one then reading the other usually isn’t too difficult with a bit of exposure.

